english:
  title: A Sequence Seeing Off Commandant Jeong
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Commandant Jeong Yeong-se of Hanyang was departing for the provincial office when ten intimate friends gathered at the eastern fields to bid him farewell. Once the wine had begun to circulate, Commandant Jeong rose, bowed, and spoke: "When friends send off a departing companion with words, surely it amounts to more than merely offering wine." I promptly replied:

    "Hanyang is a great garrison beyond the capital's walls, anciently called Namkyeong, standing as one leg of a tripod alongside the Eastern and Western capitals. It was once the seat of our predecessors, its mountains and rivers as majestic, its people as flourishing as the royal city itself. Therefore, those appointed to govern it must possess both towering character and commanding reputation to earn the people's trust. The same applies to their attendants and advisors.

    Since the kingdom has faced calamities and times have grown unlike the ancients, shame and honor have withered from the land. Above and below scheme only for profit. The powerful seize and consolidate holdings; cruel officials follow suit with harsh taxation. Not an inch of earth remains free from seizure, and families sing songs of empty coffers. Magistrates sit watching yet dare not speak, exhorting the people only to fill their own bellies. The people's suffering and despair have never been worse than now. The regions surrounding the capital for hundreds of li suffer most terribly. What was called Namkyeong grows ever more desolate—mere thorny wastes with but eight or nine households remaining. Other districts need hardly be mentioned.

    Are there not one or two with hearts devoted to the people? Yet all merely follow custom and make do with expediency. But you, Commandant, possess both talent and youth, and have gained a benevolent and worthy governor as your superior. With his approval, you may pursue your noble ambitions—promoting benefit and eliminating harm, so that the sounds of music and the voices of contented people resound throughout your region and reach the distant corners.

    Some say: 'A commandant's post is humble; deep-rooted evils cannot be swiftly remedied.' This is profoundly mistaken. When one family practices goodness, a whole nation tends toward goodness. The superior person need only exhaust their own effort. Should you truly exhaust your effort and make the people's hearts your own heart, then even if you do not achieve all, you will not fall far short. Why concern yourself with rank or the state of customs?'

    Commandant Jeong did not dismiss my words, and the others agreed as well. Thus I record this as a preface to the poems that follow.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Hanyang (漢陽), also called Namkyeong (南京, Southern Capital), was an important administrative center in medieval Korea, comparable to Pyongyang in its historical significance.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three capitals standing like a tripod' refers to the Eastern Capital, Western Capital, and Hanyang, suggesting their equal importance to the kingdom.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'sounds of music and voices of contented people' is a classical allusion to good governance, drawing from Confucian ideals of virtuous rule.
  - key: ''
    value: This sequence was written as a preface to a collection of farewell poems composed by the ten friends attending the gathering.
